text: i feel like they could've done the female-empowerment trope much more effectively. like, it's great to see the plot involving less-helpless victims, but revealing all the differences from the original IN THE TRAILER is always a mistake. now everyone knows there's a machismo-fueled rivalry: secret society bros vs. what they view to be the weaker sex.   the premise could've so easily been flipped by having the killer hunt this secret society frat (who have terrorized women for decades) instead, all while keeping the original's methodic, skin-crawling atmosphere intact. at the climax, reveal the killer to be an abused woman (or women) who use(s) her/their intelligence and cunning and honed physical strength to take down the notorious and dangerous house that has wronged her/them/countless others). you could even rework the helplessness plot-point from the original by having several of them fake their own deaths.   don't get me wrong: there's nothing like watching powerful, arrogant antagonists get their comeuppance. i just wish it hadn't been spoiled halfway through the trailer.

Obviously the writers have not done their research, because, while slasher films have historically objectified women on a corporeal level, they have also nearly always made women the heroes of those stories. This remake does not appear to be nearly as subversive as it thinks it is.

text: I don't normally like to complain about trailers spoiling the entire movie because its a fairly overrated complaint but I have to say this is literally laughable how the films plot twist is told to us in the trailer. Its possible that there is more to the movie but considering that this is a remake of a pretty straight forward slasher film from the 70s which featured one killer picking off girls one at a time like in most traditional slasher films then the idea of some sort of christmas cult would have come as a surprise for those familiar with the original but that wont be the case now thanks to this trailer. I also find it questionable as to why this film looks much campier in tone with the 2006 remake rather than the originals more simple tone. I'm not even a fan of the original film nor the 2006 remake and it looks like this will be yet another let down from the hit or miss studio known as Blum House.
